  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal or \"clean\". This typically involves disguising the true origin of the funds, often through complex transactions or financial maneuvers.\n\nIn China, the legal framework against money laundering is robust and strictly enforced. The country has enacted specific laws and regulations to combat money laundering, such as the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was first adopted in 2006 and has been updated to address emerging threats. Additionally, China is an active member of international organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nUnder Chinese law, money laundering is punishable by severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and other entities are also required to implement anti-money laundering measures, such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and maintaining records.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally recognized as an illegal activity under both Chinese and international legal systems, and efforts to combat it are a priority for law enforcement and regulatory authorities.",
